Finding Electricity Curve Codes¶

Filtering by the Electricity MDC and curves that have an hourly frequency. Further filtering by a few cities for this example

In [5]:
fc = ci.ForwardCurves()
In [6]:
curves = fc.get_curves(
    mdc="ET",
    derivative_maturity_frequency=fc.MatFrequency.Hour,
    delivery_region=["Leipzig", "Paris", "Vienna"],
)

Getting Assessments¶

group curves together by delivery region andn fetch assessments for the past year.

storing in a dictionary df for ease-of-use.

In [7]:
grp = curves.groupby("delivery_region")["curve_code"].apply(list)
grp
Out[7]:
delivery_region
Leipzig    [CN2IS, CN2IR]
Paris      [CN2IO, CN2IN]
Vienna     [CN2IV, CN2IU]
Name: curve_code, dtype: object
In [8]:
df = {}
today = date.today()
one_year_ago = today.replace(year=today.year - 1)
for city, codes in grp.items():
    df[city] = fc.get_assessments(
        curve_code=codes, paginate=True, assess_date_gte=one_year_ago
    )

More Plotting¶

Let's use faceting to show the volume and the price side-by-side and show different time periods

  • by quarter
  • weekday vs weekend
  • by month

adding the relevant columns to our dataframes

In [13]:
for _, v in df.items():
    v["quarter"] = v["assessDate"].dt.quarter
    v["day_of_week"] = v["assessDate"].dt.weekday
    v["is_weekend"] = v["day_of_week"] > 4
    v["month"] = v["assessDate"].dt.strftime("%B %Y")

Let's turn this into a function so we can re-use it with several optional parameters.

Here for EPEX Germany (Leipzig)

In [16]:
def strip_plot(
    data: pd.DataFrame,
    col: str,
    col_wrap: int = None,
    row: str = None,
    col_template: str = "Q{col_name}",
    aspect: int = 2,
):
    g = sns.FacetGrid(
        data=data, col=col, row=row, col_wrap=col_wrap, aspect=aspect, sharey="row"
    ).set_titles(row_template="{row_name}", col_template=col_template)
    g.map_dataframe(
        sns.stripplot, x="derivative_position", y="value", alpha=0.5
    ).set_xlabels("Hour")


strip_plot(df["Leipzig"], col="quarter", row="curve_name")
